solutions.content:
Hello everyone, recursion on tree is hard to understand, but hope this answer can give you some intuition.

I figure it will be helpful to **only think of a simplest tree** when it comes recusion on tree. Concretly, think **a node with only a left child node and right child node**. What would the code look like if we want to do inorder-traversal. Answer is:
```
// Because it is just a simplest tree, we can write like this.
void inorder(TreeNode *root){
	cout << root->left->val;
	cout << root->val;
	cout << root->right>val;
}
```
Ok, so far so well. But remember, the tree in real question is always not so simple. And that's why we use recursion.

Now, we **keep** the operation we did **for the current node** and **replace** the **left and right** operation with **recursion as operation of current node**, because this time we see left and right as subtree rather than node. 

And every time we enter a subtree, we face the same situation as its parent, that's why we keep the current node operation and replace others, **we only have to and only CAN deal with the current node directly**, we can't deal with subtree directly. Code like this:
```
// This time we face a real complicated tree. And just deal with some edge case when root is nullptr.
void inorder(TreeNode *root){
	if(root == nullptr) return; // edge case and for the stop of recursion.
	inorder(root->left); // replace
	cout << root->val; // keep
	inorder(root->right); // replace
}
```
OK, take a breath and let's look at this question. The first thing you should know is **the result of inorder-traversal of a BST is an ordered sequence**. Go and search google or check MIT OCW 6.006 lecture05 if you are not familiar with BST.

Welcome back and we move on, just think of it is a simplest tree in this question, and code should be:
```
class Solution {
 public:
	TreeNode* increasingBST(TreeNode* root) {
		solve(root);
		return ret;
	}

private:
	TreeNode *ret = nullptr; // record left-most TreeNode
	TreeNode *pre = nullptr; // record pre TreeNode
	void solve(TreeNode *root){
		ret = root->left; // ret is the left-most node.
		pre = ret; // initialize pre
		pre->right = root; // just keep right node of pre is current node.
		root->left = nullptr; 
		pre = root; // we have go through root, let's mark root as pre and move on.
		// same operation bellow
		pre->right = root->right;
		root->right->left = nullptr;
		pre = root->right;
	}
};
```

OK, hope you have understood the solution for the simplest BST. There are just few things to do next.
First keep the operation for current node which are:
```
// in the view of current node, we have recorded pre node.
pre->right = root;
root->left = nullptr;
pre = root;
```
**ret** is the left-most TreeNode, and we want to return it at last. How can we get it? At very beginning, we initialize **pre** as nullptr, that makes sense because there is no pre node. And after we see first current node, we assign current code to pre. 

So we can use the state of pre to get ret. We check whether pre is nullptr or not, if it is, we know the node that we currently deal with is the first node (**first is also the left-most** based on the observation of simplest BST), and we assign it to ret. Code now looks like:
```
if(pre){
	pre->right = root;
}else{
	ret = root;
}
root->left = nullptr;
pre = root;
```
The rest code is just trivial. We add two recursion for left subtree and right subtree and the edge case to stop recursion. Total code is there:
```
class Solution {
 public:
	TreeNode* increasingBST(TreeNode* root) {
		solve(root);
		return ret;
	}
private:
    TreeNode *ret = nullptr;
    TreeNode *pre = nullptr;
    void solve(TreeNode *root){
        if(root == nullptr) return; // edge case and for the stop of recursion.
        solve(root->left); // recursion on left subtree.
		if(pre){
			pre->right = root;
		}else{
			ret = root;
		}
		root->left = nullptr;
		pre = root;
        solve(root->right); //recursion on right subtree.
    }
};
```

Have a good day.

By,
Aincrad-Lyu

