solutions.content:
Recursive approach with class-level variable to keep previous node is fairly simple. I decided to do it without recursion to refresh on how in-order traversal is done iteratively using stack + extra pointer. Overall, this exercise has good take-aways:
* Pre-head pointer technique used in many problems, esp. linked list related
* Iterative in-order traversal mixed with custom logic
* Corner case analysis (easy to miss out to clear left child of the last node)

```
class Solution {
    public TreeNode increasingBST(TreeNode root) {
        TreeNode preRoot = new TreeNode();
        TreeNode prev = preRoot;

        TreeNode curr = root;
        Deque<TreeNode> stack = new ArrayDeque<>();

        // classic stack+current approach for non-recursive in-order traversal
        while (curr != null || !stack.isEmpty()) {
            while (curr != null) {
                stack.push(curr);
                curr = curr.left;
            }

            curr = stack.pop();

            // link previous node with current one (and detach it from left branch)
            prev.right = curr;
            prev.left = null;

            // current node becomes previous
            prev = curr;

            // this is transition within in-order traversal
            // (next iteration will use either stack of switch over to curr if it's not null)
            curr = curr.right;
        }
        // this is tricky corner case:
        prev.left = null;

        // prev.right is already null since it's the last node within in-order traversal

        return preRoot.right;
    }
}
```

