We can simplify the problem by assuming that we have solution for left subtree and right subtree for a given node. This means that left subtree has the following structure 1->2->3->4 and right subtree has the following structure 6->7->8->9. Now we only have to link 4 to 5 and 5 to 6 and we are done.
On solving the subproblem we return the leftmost node and rightmost node in an array. This is useful as we need rightmost node of the left subtree and leftmost node of right subtree to link the two subproblems.
TBH this was not an easy problem. What do you guys think?
```
class Solution {
    public TreeNode increasingBST(TreeNode root) {
        return helper(root)[0];
    }

    private TreeNode[] helper(TreeNode node) {
        if (node == null) { 
            return new TreeNode[]{null, null};
        }
        TreeNode[] leftSubtree = helper(node.left);
        if (leftSubtree[1] != null) {
            leftSubtree[1].right = node;
        }
        if (leftSubtree[0] == null) {
            leftSubtree[0] = node;
        }

        node.left = null;

        TreeNode[] rightSubTree = helper(node.right);
        if (rightSubTree[0] != null) {
            node.right = rightSubTree[0];
        }
        if (rightSubTree[1] == null) {
            rightSubTree[1] = node;
        }

        return new TreeNode[]{leftSubtree[0], rightSubTree[1]};
    }
}
```

