# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The intuition is that we just need to do the level order traversal starting from level 0 till level **"level"** and then get the videos watched by the **friends at this level** in the desired order.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Here, I'm using the **queue** data structure to store the pair<int,int> denoting **{level,friends}** and then do a simple **BFS** at all the friends at adjacent level and when we reach at level **"level"**, we are storing the friends in the array **nodes**. Also, to keep track of the already visited friends, we are using a visited array and then finally, to get the final array of strings in the desired order, I'm creating a hashmap to get the frequency of the videos and then using a set to have them sorted in the order of their frequencies and lexicographically for videos having same frequency.


# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<string> watchedVideosByFriends(vector<vector<string>>& watchedVideos, vector<vector<int>>& friends, int id, int level) {

        int n = friends.size();

        queue<pair<int,int>> q;
        vector<bool> visited(n,false);
        q.push({0,id});
        visited[id] = true;

        vector<int> nodes;

        while(!q.empty()) {
            auto it = q.front();
            q.pop();

            int curr_level = it.first;
            int curr_id = it.second;

            if(curr_level == level) {
                nodes.push_back(curr_id);
                continue;
            }

            for(auto &i:friends[curr_id]) {
                if(visited[i]) continue;
                q.push({curr_level+1,i});
                visited[i] = true;
            }
        }

        unordered_map<string,int> frequency;
        for(auto &i:nodes) {
            for(auto &j:watchedVideos[i]) frequency[j]++;
        }

        set<pair<int,string>> st;
        for(auto &i:frequency) st.insert({i.second,i.first});

        vector<string> ans;
        for(auto &i:st) ans.push_back(i.second);

        return ans; 
    }
};
```

