solutions.content:
I was thinking about whether there is any greedy strategy to directly solve this rather than searching. But I decided to use a brute-force backtracking as the size is limited with in 20... 
Once we find the valid solution, stop the backtracking and restore of the array to get the desired solution. This may help to improve the speed. I think the complexity should be O(n!). Please correct me if I'm wrong.

```
class Solution {
    public int[] constructDistancedSequence(int n) {
        int[] res = new int[2 * n - 1];
        boolean[] used = new boolean[n+1];
        dfs(0, res, used);
        return res;
    }

    public boolean dfs(int idx, int[] res, boolean[] used) {
        if (idx == res.length) { // we have get the valid solution, yeah!
            return true;
        }

        if (res[idx] != 0) { // current position has been used, check the next one
            return dfs(idx+1, res, used);
        }

        // backtracking logic
        for (int n = used.length - 1; n > 0; n--) {
            // checking logic here:
            // 1. n is not used
            // 2. (idx + n) the index of the duplication must be valid
            // 3. res[idx + n] has NOT be used
            if (!used[n] && (n == 1 || idx+n < res.length && res[idx+n] == 0)) {
                res[idx] = n;
                if (n != 1) res[idx+n] = n;
                used[n] = true;
                if (dfs(idx+1, res, used)) return true;
                res[idx] = 0;
                if (n != 1)  res[idx+n] = 0;
                used[n] = false;
            }
        }

        return false;
    }
}
