# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
We need to always consider the next biggest number we can use and perfectly place each and every number around it satisfying the conditions given in the problem. We could understand it as Greedy BackTracking

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
As we need to try out different combinations, the natural solution is recursion and backtracking so as to keep trying different combinations and use the appropriate one.
The base case is the usual whenever we are trying all the combinations , we make the combination and when we are through with it we check if it fits our conditions, so as we did not need any unfilled element we counted if there were any 0's present.

We also iterate everytime from n to 1 while keeping a check on those elements which we haven't visited so as to not fill them again and if we do not find a matching combination we back track and fill some other element.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
Exponential although not Factorial due to our constraints of |i - j| 

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O(n)$$ due to the visited vector + Recursive Stack Space

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    bool backTrack(vector<int>& vec, int p, int n, vector<bool>& vis, int sz)
    {
        if(p == sz)
        {
            if(count(vec.begin(), vec.end(), 0) == 0)
                return true;
            return false;
        }
        for(int i = n; i >= 1; i--)
        {
            if(i == 1 && vec[p] == 0 && vis[i] == false)
            {
                vis[i] = true;
                vec[p] = i;
                if(backTrack(vec, p + 1, n, vis, sz))
                    return true;
                vis[i] = false;
                vec[p] = 0;
            }
            else if(p + i < sz && vec[p] == 0 && vec[p + i] == 0 && vis[i] == false)
            {
                vis[i] = true;
                vec[p] = vec[p + i] = i;
                if(backTrack(vec, p + 1, n, vis, sz))
                    return true;
                vis[i] = false;
                vec[p] = vec[p + i] = 0;
            }
        }
        if(count(vec.begin(), vec.end(), 0) == 0)
            return true;
        return backTrack(vec, p + 1, n, vis, sz);
    }
    vector<int> constructDistancedSequence(int n) {
        int size = 2 * n - 1;
        vector<int> vec(size, 0);
        vector<bool> vis(n + 1, false);
        bool what = backTrack(vec, 0, n, vis, size);
        return vec;
    }
};
```

